Is it easier to say to this man, "Your sins are forgiven," or to say, "Get up, take your bed and walk"?
"I want you to know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins." Then Jesus said to the paralytic, "Get up, take your mat and go home."
"I'm telling you," he said, "get up. Take your mat and go home."
The man got up, took his mat, and walked away, while everyone was watching. They were all astounded, and they praised God, saying, "We have never seen anything like this before!" Jesus chooses Levi.
And Jesus went again to the seashore of Galilee, where a large crowd gathered around Him, and He began to teach them.
As Jesus went on from there, he saw a man named Levi sitting at the tax collector's booth. "Follow me," he told him, and Levi got up and followed him.
And afterward Jesus was sitting at a table in the house of Levi. And many tax collectors and "sinners" were eating with him and his disciples. For there were many who were following Jesus.
And there were some teachers of the law among the Pharisees who saw Jesus eating with "sinners" and tax collectors. So they asked his disciples, "Why does he eat with tax collectors and 'sinners'?"
And Jesus heard it, and said unto them, "They that are whole have no need of the physician, but they that are sick: I came not to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance." He was asked about fasting.
