On the Sabbath, Jesus was walking through the wheat fields with his disciples. The disciples began to pick some of the heads of wheat.
The Pharisees said to Jesus, "Look! It is not lawful to do these things on the Sabbath. Why do your disciples do this?"
He replied, "Have you never read what David did? He and his men were hungry. They needed food.
It was at the time when Abiathar was high priest. David entered the house of God and ate the consecrated bread. Only the priests were allowed to eat it. And he also gave some to his men.
Then Jesus said to them, "The Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath."
"The Son of Man is Lord of the Sabbath also."
Healing on Saturday
Jesus went again into the synagogue, and there was a man there whose hand was withered.
Some Pharisees were trying to find fault with Jesus. They were watching him closely. They wanted to see whether he would heal the man on the Sabbath.
Jesus spoke to the man with the weak and withered hand. He said to him, "Stand up in front of everyone."
Then Jesus asked them, "What does the law say about what we should do on the Sabbath? Is it right to do good or to do evil? To save a life or to kill?" But no one answered.
Jesus looked around at them with anger. He was deeply disturbed because their hearts were hard. Then he said to the man, "Stretch out your hand." He stretched it out, and his hand was restored, just like new.
Then the Pharisees went out and began to plot with the Herodians against Jesus, how they might destroy Him. The multitudes followed Jesus.
Jesus went with his disciples to the Sea of Galilee, and a large crowd from Galilee followed him.
When the people heard all that Jesus was doing, many came to him. They came from Judea, Jerusalem, Idumea, beyond the Jordan, and the region around Tyre and Sidon.
Because of the crowd, Jesus asked his disciples to prepare a small boat for him. This was to prevent the people from crowding around him.
Jesus healed many people. So the sick rushed forward to touch him.
And when the unclean spirits saw him, they fell down before him, and cried, saying, Thou art the Son of God.
But Jesus commanded them to tell no one who he was. The appointment of the twelve apostles by Jesus.
Jesus went up the mountain and called to him those he wanted, and they came to him.
He appointed twelve, whom he also named apostles, that they might be with him and he might send them out to preach.
And they will have authority to cast out demons.
So Jesus chose twelve, and Simon was one of them. He named him Peter.
There was James son of Zebedee and his brother John. Jesus gave them the name Boanerges, which means Sons of Thunder.
And Andrew, and Philip, and Bartholomew, and Matthew, and Thomas, and James the son of Alphaeus, and Thaddaeus, and Simon the Zealot.
